qas.question: The Slavs from Kievan would eventually settle in the North East of the region, What would this region later become?
What was the name of the oldest city in the north east?
In what year did the mongol invasion begin?
How did the Slavs form the Grand Duchy of Moscow in the southeast?
What is the youngest centre in the southeast?
What city did Prince Andrey Bogolyuskiy sack in the 12th century?
Who did not take the title of Grand Prince?
When did Vladimir-Suzdal assert itself as a minor power?

context: In the northeast, Slavs from the Kievan region <b3_0>colonized the territory<b3_0/> that later would become the <a0_0>Grand Duchy of Moscow<a0_0/> by subjugating and merging with the Finnic tribes already occupying the area. The city of <a1_0><b4_0>Rostov<b4_0/><a1_0/>, the oldest centre of the northeast, was supplanted first by Suzdal and then by the city of Vladimir, which become the capital of Vladimir-Suzdal'. The combined principality of Vladimir-Suzdal asserted itself as a major power in Kievan Rus' in the <b7_0>late 12th century<b7_0/>. In 1169 <b6_0>Prince Andrey Bogolyubskiy<b6_0/> of Vladimir-Suzdal sacked the city of <b5_0>Kiev<b5_0/> and took over the title of the (Великий Князь/Velikiy Knyaz/Grand Prince or Grand Duke) to Vladimir, this way claiming the primacy in Rus'. Prince Andrey then installed his younger brother, who ruled briefly in Kiev while Andrey continued to rule his realm from Suzdal. <a2_0>In 1299<a2_0/>, in the wake of the Mongol invasion, the metropolitan moved from Kiev to the city of Vladimir and Vladimir-Suzdal.
